      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The phenomenon you're describing is often referred to as \"widow making\" or \"underutilized capacity\" - systems can become too optimized and lack the flexibility to handle unexpected events. It's not uncommon for engineers to be unaware of this when their systems are humming along just fine, but it's often the moments of high stress or chaos that reveal the weaknesses. Coincidentally, being in \"spot time\", tweaking nodes and trying out new protocols, likely caught the system off-guard, making it more vulnerable to cascading failures.",
